`creditSettlement` is called from the API controller at [OrderController.php:222](/Users/naman/Documents/QBApps/qbapi/app/Http/Controllers/OrderController.php#L222) and the real settlement logic is in [Order.php:2581](/Users/naman/Documents/QBApps/qbapi/app/Order.php#L2581). There is a second entry into the same flow from `postAdvancePayment()` at [Order.php:3504](/Users/naman/Documents/QBApps/qbapi/app/Order.php#L3504), which auto-builds an unpaid-order list and then calls `self::creditSettlement(...)` at [Order.php:3621](/Users/naman/Documents/QBApps/qbapi/app/Order.php#L3621).

Before the fix, `isNoCharge` was not actually enforced in settlement. The controller even populates `isNoCharge = 0` in the payload at [OrderController.php:848](/Users/naman/Documents/QBApps/qbapi/app/Http/Controllers/OrderController.php#L848), but `creditSettlement()` did not use that field. That meant `isNoCharge=1` orders could still enter settlement, and settlement would process them like normal credit-sale orders: reduce `PAYMENT_CREDIT`, insert new payment/accounting rows, and update balances. That is the double-counting path.

The exact fix needed is already present as local uncommitted changes in [Order.php](/Users/naman/Documents/QBApps/qbapi/app/Order.php):

